40:43.341 --> 40:47.745 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
short term to create exactly the
sort of death
spiral and destabilization that
we're all

40:47.779 --> 40:49.647 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
worried about.

40:49.681 --> 40:52.850 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so it seems to me and it
seems to a growing
number of Republican senators,
including Bob

40:52.884 --> 40:56.688 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Corker and John McCain, that you
have got
to repeal and replace at the
same time.

40:56.721 --> 41:00.725 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You have to have a plan, or else
you're just
creating a recipe for chaos.

41:00.758 --> 41:04.996 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's not clear how much
either the House
leadership or the Trump
administration has

41:05.029 --> 41:07.465 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
thought that through how exactly
how it's
going to work.

41:07.498 --> 41:08.900 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Just 10 seconds,
Mark.

41:08.933 --> 41:09.901 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We will be watching.

41:09.934 --> 41:11.235 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: What's the big
rush, Judy?

41:11.269 --> 41:13.604 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What's the big rush on the
health care plan?

41:13.638 --> 41:15.373 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's been eight years.

41:15.406 --> 41:17.241 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So they have had a lot of ideas.

41:17.275 --> 41:19.277 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I mean, Paul Ryan said that.

41:19.310 --> 41:20.845 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They have got ideas everywhere.

41:20.878 --> 41:24.282 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They have no idea what they're
going to do.

41:24.315 --> 41:25.783 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Repeal is low-hanging fruit.

41:25.817 --> 41:26.784 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
They have done it.

41:26.818 --> 41:27.785 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They have done it 60 times.

41:27.819 --> 41:28.920 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
They will do it 60 more.

41:28.953 --> 41:30.188 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
They have no plan.

41:30.221 --> 41:40.264 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Mark Shields,
David Brooks,
thank you both.

41:40.264 --> 41:45.103 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Mark Shields,
David Brooks,
thank you both.

41:45.136 --> 41:51.142 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now the latest story in our
series about food
in America, a collaboration
between the "NewsHour"

41:51.175 --> 41:52.944 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
and NPR.

41:52.977 --> 41:58.316 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Tonight, our focus is on
seafood, and specifically
a movement to ensure sustainable
seafood.

41:58.349 --> 42:03.988 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
That means fish caught
domestically and locally,
and not fished to extinction.

42:04.021 --> 42:08.593 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Despite the vast expanse of
shoreline in this
country, more than 90 percent of
the seafood

42:08.626 --> 42:11.496 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Americans eat is imported.

42:11.529 --> 42:15.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Many conservationists, fishermen
and foodies
are out to change this.

42:15.967 --> 42:20.805 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Special correspondent Allison
Aubrey of NPR
News has the story.

42:20.838 --> 42:26.911 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALLISON AUBREY: Cape Cod,
Massachusetts, named
for the cod, but that's not what
fisherman

42:26.944 --> 42:29.347 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Jamie Eldredge is catching
today.

42:29.380 --> 42:31.749 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Cod's been overfished in these
waters.

42:31.783 --> 42:37.688 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now he's laying his lines for a
fish that
most American's have never even
heard of.

42:37.722 --> 42:40.491 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's called dogfish.

42:40.525 --> 42:41.492 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And was it a good catch?

42:41.526 --> 42:43.428 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
How much did you land?

42:43.461 --> 42:45.863 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAMIE ELDREDGE, Fisherman: It's
a daily limit
of 6,000 pounds, and probably
was just a little

42:45.897 --> 42:47.598 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
shy of it today.

42:47.632 --> 42:51.469 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALLISON AUBREY: That fish ends
up here at
this processing plant just up
the road.

42:51.502 --> 42:55.740 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, this is dogfish here, kind
of a long sharky-looking
thing?

42:55.773 --> 42:58.009 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BRIAN MARDER, Owner, Marder
Trawling: Yes.

42:58.042 --> 43:01.846 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Yes, it is the most plentiful
fish we have
on the East Coast right now.

43:01.879 --> 43:06.217 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALLISON AUBREY: Owner Brian
Marder says the
Chatham fishermen will bring in
six million

43:06.250 --> 43:08.119 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
pounds of dogfish this year.

43:08.152 --> 43:11.889 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
His operation turns that spiky
shark into
long white fillets.

43:11.923 --> 43:13.357 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Who's buying this fish?

43:13.391 --> 43:16.561 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BRIAN MARDER: This is all being
packed for
the European export market.

43:16.594 --> 43:17.695 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALLISON AUBREY: I'm told that
the French love
it.

43:17.728 --> 43:18.696 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
They call it salmonetes.

43:18.729 --> 43:19.697 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
BRIAN MARDER: Salmonete, yes.

43:19.730 --> 43:21.399 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ALLISON AUBREY: Which sounds
kind of fancy.

43:21.432 --> 43:23.401 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
BRIAN MARDER: Yes.

43:23.434 --> 43:25.603 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALLISON AUBREY: Are you telling
me that everything
being processed here is just
going to be shipped

43:25.636 --> 43:26.604 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
out?

43:26.637 --> 43:27.605 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
BRIAN MARDER: Yes, it is.

43:27.638 --> 43:28.606 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ALLISON AUBREY: Ninety-nine
percent of it?

43:28.639 --> 43:30.408 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BRIAN MARDER: Ninety-nine
percent.

43:30.441 --> 43:33.778 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALLISON AUBREY: While all this
dogfish is
shipping out to Europe, where's
the fish that

43:33.811 --> 43:37.815 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Americans like to eat coming
from?

43:37.849 --> 43:43.087 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Turns out it's being flown in
from countries
around the world, arriving at
warehouses like

43:43.120 --> 43:44.622 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
this one we visited.

43:44.655 --> 43:48.493 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Santa Monica Seafood is one of
the largest
distributors on the West Coast.

43:48.526 --> 43:53.331 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This year, they will distribute
42 million
pounds of seafood, much of it
imported.

43:53.364 --> 43:58.135 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Lots of fresh caught seafood
going out and
tons of seafood coming in from
overseas, it's

43:58.169 --> 44:03.107 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a swap that plays out across the
United States,
according to Jennifer Dianto
Kemmerly Bio.

44:03.140 --> 44:06.344 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She's director of Seafood Watch
at the Monterey
Bay Aquarium.

44:06.377 --> 44:09.313 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
They track and rank
environmentally responsible
fisheries.

44:09.347 --> 44:12.183 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JENNIFER DIANTO KEMMERLY,
Monterey Bay Aquarium:
Over 90 percent of the seafood
we consume

44:12.216 --> 44:16.454 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the U.S. is actually caught
or farm-raised
overseas.

44:16.487 --> 44:20.124 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the majority of the seafood
that we catch
in our U.S. fisheries doesn't
stay here in

44:20.157 --> 44:21.125 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
our local market.

44:21.158 --> 44:22.126 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It goes to other countries.

44:22.159 --> 44:24.028 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ALLISON AUBREY: Does that make
sense?

44:24.061 --> 44:26.898 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JENNIFER DIANTO KEMMERLY: We're
kind of missing
out on the bounty that we
actually have here.

44:26.931 --> 44:30.902 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We're not celebrating the local
fisheries
as much as we probably should
be.

44:30.935 --> 44:35.473 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALLISON AUBREY: And that bounty
is so plentiful,
the Environmental Defense Fund
has launched

44:35.506 --> 44:41.579 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a campaign to get Americans
eating these lesser-known
species from our own coastal
waters.

44:41.612 --> 44:46.150 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NARRATOR: Eat These Fish is a
campaign to
celebrate the comeback of
America's fisheries.

44:46.183 --> 44:51.689 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
ALLISON AUBREY: Like New
England's overfished
cod, fisheries around the U.S.
were being

44:51.722 --> 44:53.524 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
depleted.

44:53.558 --> 44:57.562 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
After environmentalists sounded
alarm bells,
Congress passed an act in 2006
that required

44:57.595 --> 45:00.798 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
fisheries to set quotas by 2011.

45:00.831 --> 45:02.900 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Now fisheries have rebounded.

45:02.934 --> 45:07.204 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Nancy Civetta is with the Cape
Cod Commercial
Fishermen's Alliance.

45:07.238 --> 45:09.974 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She's been trying to promote the
story of
dogfish.

45:10.007 --> 45:15.079 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She says even with all the
demand from Europe,
there's still plenty left here
for Americans

45:15.112 --> 45:16.914 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
to eat.

45:16.948 --> 45:18.149 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
NANCY CIVETTA, Cape Cod
Commercial Fishermen's
Alliance: There's so many out
there, that

45:18.182 --> 45:20.184 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
we don't even catch the quota
the government
allows us.

45:20.217 --> 45:22.219 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ALLISON AUBREY: But here's the
challenge.

45:22.253 --> 45:24.922 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NANCY CIVETTA: We don't eat
dogfish in this
country.

45:24.956 --> 45:29.460 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We import salmon, tuna and
shrimp.

45:29.493 --> 45:33.264 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We do not eat the food that
we're bringing
to shore right here.

45:33.297 --> 45:38.769 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALLISON AUBREY: Civetta says
importing most
of the fish we eat could have
consequences

45:38.803 --> 45:40.538 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
down the line.

45:40.571 --> 45:45.176 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NANCY CIVETTA: If we continue to
import and
buy from other countries, then
our fishing

45:45.209 --> 45:47.011 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
industry could wither away.

45:47.044 --> 45:52.149 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If we're going to maximize the
potential of
this fishery, then we need to
create markets,

45:52.183 --> 45:56.454 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
so that the fisherman can fish
for it, they
can better their bottom lines,
and we can

45:56.487 --> 45:58.255 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
have a sustainable coastal
community.

45:58.289 --> 46:02.927 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SEAN DIMIN, Sea to Table: So
what they do
is they lay down on the bottom
of the ocean.

46:02.960 --> 46:07.531 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALLISON AUBREY: Sean Dimin runs
a company
called Sea to Table that he says
is doing

46:07.565 --> 46:09.367 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
just that.

46:09.400 --> 46:12.570 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SEAN DIMIN: We come out here to
places like
Chatham, fishing communities all
around America's

46:12.603 --> 46:18.009 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
coasts, and we figure out how to
get the best
directly to chefs, universities,
distributing

46:18.042 --> 46:23.514 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
directly from the point of catch
to the point
of consumption.

46:23.547 --> 46:28.519 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Beautiful photos of the fish
that we can now
sell directly to people's homes.

46:28.552 --> 46:33.691 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALLISON AUBREY: Back at Sea to
Table's Brooklyn
headquarters, Dimin explains
that his operation

46:33.724 --> 46:36.394 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is a complete departure from the
traditional
model.

46:36.427 --> 46:42.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SEAN DIMIN: A big thing that we
do is sell
fish that fishermen are
catching, not necessarily

46:42.667 --> 46:46.103 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
what American consumers and
diners think they
want.

46:46.137 --> 46:49.273 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that's a big part of what we
do is supporting
American fishing communities.

46:49.306 --> 46:50.274 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MAN: That's beautiful.

46:50.307 --> 46:52.109 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
MAN: Yes.

46:52.143 --> 46:55.946 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALLISON AUBREY: And the model
aligns perfectly
with a big push at university
dining halls

46:55.980 --> 46:59.083 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to source their foods from more
local and
sustainable sources.

46:59.116 --> 47:01.018 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MAN: On the count of three, say
dogfish.

47:01.052 --> 47:04.588 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALLISON AUBREY: This group runs
the dining
halls at the University of
Massachusetts.

47:04.622 --> 47:08.359 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They serve 55,000 meals a day.

47:08.392 --> 47:13.531 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They have made a commitment to
bring this
dogfish and other underloved
fish back to

47:13.564 --> 47:15.332 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
their campus.

47:15.366 --> 47:19.603 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's at university dining halls
like this
one, where thousands of people
eat every day,

47:19.637 --> 47:21.706 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that you might be able to shake
things up.

47:21.739 --> 47:27.344 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
These students are used to
trying new things,
and a lot of them love the
novelty of it.

47:27.378 --> 47:28.913 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So what's the appeal here?

47:28.946 --> 47:31.182 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Why go out of the way to buy
dogfish?

47:31.215 --> 47:34.218 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BOB BANKERT, Chef, University of
Massachusetts:
Being in Western Massachusetts,
we love to

47:34.251 --> 47:37.722 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
support the Massachusetts
fisheries, and that
it tastes great.

47:37.755 --> 47:42.793 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALLISON AUBREY: University of
Massachusetts
chef Bob Bankert is grilling
dogfish fillets.

47:42.827 --> 47:48.332 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's lathered them in a spicy
seasoning to
make tacos.

47:48.365 --> 47:52.703 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
At another food station, the
dogfish becomes
an Asian flash fry.

47:52.737 --> 47:56.974 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's drizzled with wasabi mayo
on top.

47:57.007 --> 47:58.843 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
The students are curious.

47:58.876 --> 48:03.948 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A display tells them where the
dogfish comes
from and who caught it.

48:03.981 --> 48:05.950 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Selina Fournier is manager of
this dining
hall.

48:05.983 --> 48:07.752 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SELINA FOURNIER, Dining Hall
Manager, University
of Massachusetts: There's
students that may

48:07.785 --> 48:11.989 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have never heard of such a fish,
and so when
they saw the fish here today,
and then got

48:12.022 --> 48:17.428 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
to taste it, the whole
association really
creates that story and bringing
it to life,

48:17.461 --> 48:21.098 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and hopefully creating something
exciting
that they will want to order
even when they're

48:21.132 --> 48:22.933 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
not at UMass.

48:22.967 --> 48:25.236 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALLISON AUBREY: Is that your
hope, that you're
sort of setting a new generation
of eating

48:25.269 --> 48:26.237 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
habits here?

48:26.270 --> 48:28.072 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
SELINA FOURNIER: Definitely.

48:28.105 --> 48:31.809 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We are setting the standard for
the way that
these students hopefully
continue their health

48:31.842 --> 48:34.011 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and wellness once they graduate
UMass.

48:34.044 --> 48:35.780 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
WOMAN: Thank you.

48:35.813 --> 48:38.849 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALLISON AUBREY: Ruth Crawford
(ph) and Ana
Yrazusta (ph) went for the Asian
flash fry.

48:38.883 --> 48:40.885 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
So, give it a try.

48:40.918 --> 48:42.920 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Tell us what you think.

48:42.953 --> 48:44.555 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
WOMAN: Oh, my God.

48:44.588 --> 48:45.823 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
WOMAN: It's so good.

48:45.856 --> 48:47.024 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
WOMAN: Amazing.

48:47.057 --> 48:48.692 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALLISON AUBREY: What's the
biggest appeal
to you here?

48:48.726 --> 48:51.996 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOMAN: It's new, local, fresh,
so healthy.

48:52.029 --> 48:56.934 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALLISON AUBREY: Sea to Table
already has about
1,000 customers, including
dozens of large

48:56.967 --> 48:59.370 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
universities and restaurant
chefs.

48:59.403 --> 49:04.375 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they're also planning to
roll out direct-to-consumer
delivery, so people can get fish
delivered

49:04.408 --> 49:06.143 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
right to their front door.

49:06.177 --> 49:09.713 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And are you hoping now that, 10
years from
